The paper proposes a framework for disentangling local and global information within the variational autoencoder (VAE) framework, which is a popular model in machine learning and falls under the category of deep learning. The applications of the framework include deep clustering and unsupervised object detection, which are tasks related to computer vision and image processing, falling under the category of computer vision (cs.CV). The paper also discusses the benefits of disentangled representations, which are relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The experiments involve training and evaluating neural networks, which is a common technique in machine learning and falls under the category of neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE). Finally, the paper reviews cognitive neuroscience literature, which is related to natural language processing and falls under the category of computation and language (cs.CL). Overall, the most likely categories are cs.LG, cs.CV, cs.AI, cs.NE, and cs.CL, in descending order of likelihood.
